title: $A sags to six-year low after US GDP data
text:
Print 
The Australian dollar has slumped to another six-year low after the greenback rallied on US economic data. 
At 0700 AEST on Friday, the currency was trading at 72.91 US cents, down from 73.01 cents on Thursday. 
Overnight, the Aussie sagged to $72.52 US cents, its lowest level since May 2009. 
LTG GoldRock director Andrew Barnett said that although US gross domestic product was weaker than estimates, it did support slightly higher inflation, which boosted the greenback. 
"We saw a spike higher on the US dollar versus most of its major peers," he said. 
US GDP expanded at an annual rate of 2.3 per cent in the April-June period, slightly below the consensus estimate of 2.5 per cent. 
Mr Barnett said the GDP figure supported the view that the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates this year. 
"Last night's number shows there's a little glimmer of hope for inflation," he said. 
"That's what they really want - everything else is in line in the states for a rate rise." 
CURRENCY SNAPSHOT AT 0700 AEST ON FRIDAY 
One Australian dollar buys: 
* 72.91 US cents, from 73.01 cents on Thursday 
* 90.51 Japanese yen, from 90.66 yen 
* 66.69 euro cents, from 66.60 euro cents 
* 110.44 New Zealand cents, from 110.22 NZ cents 
* 46.74 British pence, from 46.79 pence 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
